properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. Temperatures continue to fall over northern Manitoba as a bitterly cold arctic airmass settles over the area. Extreme wind chill values of -45 or colder are expected to develop this evening and continue into Saturday morning. Temperatures will moderate Saturday as another system moves in from the west. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory for tonight. A cold front moving across northern Ontario tonight has brought southerly winds over lake Superior ahead of the front that has enhanced the snowfall amounts. Heavy bursts of snow and significantly reduced visibilities at times can be expected tonight. Travel along Highway 17 during this time may be hazardous. A total snowfall accumulation of 10 to 15 cm is possible by Saturday morning. Areas closer to the lake shore where the temperature is slightly above the freezing mark may accumulate less snow than areas further inland. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
